e of triumph over evil. But beneath the surface, another story was being told—one far more disturbing. And tragically, the instincts portrayed on screen — restraint, force, spectacle — still find echoes in how exorcism and deliverance are practiced, misunderstood, and sensationalized today.</p><p>Emma Schmidt was a real woman. Long before she was labeled “possessed,” she was a child—abused by her own father, betrayed by an aunt who reportedly …</p>"}